"Meinshausen M., Hare B., Wigley T.M.L., Van Vuuren D., Den Elzen M.G.J., Swart R.","Multi-gas emissions pathways to meet climate targets",2006,"Climatic Change","75","1-2",,"151","194",,,10.1007/s10584-005-9013-2,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-33745049775&partnerID=40&md5=da9c86580d1717b5c9409cc65871efcb","Swiss Federal Institute of Technology (ETH Zurich), Environmental Physics, Environmental Science Department, Rämistrasse 101, CH-8092 Zurich, Switzerland; Potsdam Institute for Climate Impact Research (PIK), Telegrafenberg A31, D-14412 Potsdam, Germany; National Center for Atmospheric Research, NCAR, P.O. Box 3000, Boulder, CO 80307, United States; Netherlands Environmental Assessment Agency (MNP), 3720 BA Bilthoven, Netherlands; EEA European Topic Center for Air and Climate Change (ETC/ACC), MNP, 3720 BA Bilthoven, Netherlands","Meinshausen, M., Swiss Federal Institute of Technology (ETH Zurich), Environmental Physics, Environmental Science Department, Rämistrasse 101, CH-8092 Zurich, Switzerland, National Center for Atmospheric Research, NCAR, P.O. Box 3000, Boulder, CO 80307, United States; Hare, B., Potsdam Institute for Climate Impact Research (PIK), Telegrafenberg A31, D-14412 Potsdam, Germany; Wigley, T.M.L., National Center for Atmospheric Research, NCAR, P.O. Box 3000, Boulder, CO 80307, United States; Van Vuuren, D., Netherlands Environmental Assessment Agency (MNP), 3720 BA Bilthoven, Netherlands; Den Elzen, M.G.J., Netherlands Environmental Assessment Agency (MNP), 3720 BA Bilthoven, Netherlands; Swart, R., EEA European Topic Center for Air and Climate Change (ETC/ACC), MNP, 3720 BA Bilthoven, Netherlands","So far, climate change mitigation pathways focus mostly on CO2 and a limited number of climate targets. Comprehensive studies of emission implications have been hindered by the absence of a flexible method to generate multi-gas emissions pathways, user-definable in shape and the climate target. The presented method 'Equal Quantile Walk' (EQW) is intended to fill this gap, building upon and complementing existing multi-gas emission scenarios. The EQW method generates new mitigation pathways by 'walking along equal quantile paths' of the emission distributions derived from existing multi-gas IPCC baseline and stabilization scenarios. Considered emissions include those of CO2 and all other major radiative forcing agents (greenhouse gases, ozone precursors and sulphur aerosols). Sample EQW pathways are derived for stabilization at 350 ppm to 750 ppm CO2 concentrations and compared to WRE profiles. Furthermore, the ability of the method to analyze emission implications in a probabilistic multi-gas framework is demonstrated. The probability of overshooting a 2°C climate target is derived by using different sets of EQW radiative forcing peaking pathways. If the probability shall not be increased above 30%, it seems necessary to peak CO2 equivalence concentrations around 475 ppm and return to lower levels after peaking (below 400 ppm). EQW emissions pathways can be applied in studies relating to Article 2 of the UNFCCC, for the analysis of climate impacts, adaptation and emission control implications associated with certain climate targets. © Springer 2006.",,"Aerosols; Carbon dioxide; Environmental impact; Greenhouse effect; Industrial emissions; Ozone layer; Probability; Sulfur; Emission control; Equal Quantile Walk (EQW); Multi gas emission; Walking along equal quantile paths; Climate change; adaptation; aerosol; climate change; emission; emission control; greenhouse gas; ozone",,,,,,"Anderson, T.L., Charlson, R.J., Schwartz, S.E., Knutti, R., Boucher, O., Rodhe, H., Heintzenberg, J., Climate forcing by aerosols a hazy picture (2003) Science, 300, pp. 1103-1104; Andronova, N.G., Schlesinger, M.E., Objective estimation of the probability density function for climate sensitivity (2001) Journal of Geophysical Research-Atmospheres, 106, pp. 22605-22611; Arnell, N.W., Cannell, M.G.R., Hulme, M., Ko